# pgauthz local configuration. Copy to `.env` and edit for your deployment:
#
#     cp .env.example .env
#
# docker compose reads `.env` automatically, and the helper scripts (env.sh,
# init.sh) source it too. The real `.env` is gitignored — keep secrets out of
# version control, and prefer a secret manager in real production. The defaults
# below reproduce the demo/dev stack, so an unset value is never a surprise.
#
# See docs/PRODUCTION.md for the full hardening checklist.

# ── Passwords (change ALL before production) ─────────────────────────────────
# Database superuser ('authz' role) — used by init.sh / admin connections.
PG_PASSWORD=authz

# Service login-role passwords. These are applied at FIRST DB init, so set them
# before the first `./init.sh`. To change them later, recreate the database:
#     docker compose down -v && ./init.sh
AUTHZEN_DIRECT_PASSWORD=authz        # decision-only pgauthzd / AuthZEN-direct connects as this reader role
PGAUTHZD_RW_PASSWORD=authz           # full (writer) pgauthzd connects as this pgauthzd_rw role
AUTHZ_WATCHER_PASSWORD=authz         # watch-API example consumer connects as this authz_watcher role (examples/watch)

# ── JWT verification (OPA + AuthZEN) ─────────────────────────────────────────
JWT_ISSUER=https://auth.example.com
JWT_AUDIENCE=authz-api

# ── Write authorization (OPA fronts the writer) ──────────────────────────────
# The pgauthzd `full`/writer instance does no JWT verification of its own; it
# trusts OPA over the service token — pgauthzd is the front door for reads AND
# writes. OPA verifies the token, then requires WRITER_ROLE within the JWT's
# roles claim, and forwards the write to the fixed-role writer instance.
# Match these two knobs to your issuer's claim shape (see docs/PRODUCTION.md):
#   JWT_ROLES_CLAIM — comma-separated dotted paths to roles arrays; roles are
#                     aggregated across all of them. Default "roles". Keycloak:
#                     "realm_access.roles,resource_access.authz-api.roles".
#   WRITER_ROLE     — role value that authorizes tuple writes (matched in any
#                     configured claim), default "authz_writer".
# JWT_ROLES_CLAIM=roles
# WRITER_ROLE=authz_writer
#
# pgauthzd `full`/writer instance OPA forwards authorized writes to. To run OPA
# READ-ONLY, omit the full instance and leave NATIVE_WRITE_URL unset; OPA's write
# rule then returns {"allowed": false, "error": "writes_disabled"}.
# NATIVE_WRITE_URL=http://pgauthzd-full:8081

# ── Read-your-writes: freshness tokens (ADR 0009) ────────────────────────────
# HMAC secret that turns on LSN-watermark freshness tokens. Set the SAME value on
# the writer (which mints a token per write) and every reader (which verifies it).
# A read then opts in with headers  X-PGAuthz-Consistency: at_least_as_fresh  +
# X-PGAuthz-Revision: <token>  — a lagging replica answers 409 + X-PGAuthz-Stale
# so the caller retries against the primary. Empty = feature off (writes mint no
# token; an at_least_as_fresh read is rejected 400, fail closed).
# FRESHNESS_TOKEN_KEY=change-me-to-a-random-secret
#
# TRANSPARENT fallback (optional): a reader-role DSN to the PRIMARY. When set on a
# decision-only reader, an at_least_as_fresh read the local replica can't satisfy
# is re-run on the primary instead of returning 409 (client sees X-PGAuthz-Served-
# By: primary). Trades reader→replica isolation for client convenience and can
# shift load to the primary — keep the pool small and watch the fallback metric.
# FRESHNESS_PRIMARY_URL=postgres://authzen_direct:authz@authz-primary:5432/authz
# FRESHNESS_PRIMARY_POOL_MAX=10

# ── Metrics (ADR 0010) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# When set, pgauthzd serves Prometheus /metrics on a SEPARATE listener (bind to
# the pod/mesh network — never the public client listener). Empty = disabled.
# Exposes HTTP RED, freshness verdict/fallback counters, build_info, and pgx pool
# stats, plus the default Go/process collectors.
# METRICS_LISTEN_ADDR=:9090

# ── AuthZEN subject policy ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# false = token-only (JWT subject authoritative; safe for user-facing APIs).
# true  = trusted PEP/PDP mode (request-body subject wins). The compose file
# defaults to false; the demo/test stack opts into true via env.sh. Leave this
# commented for the demo (env.sh handles it); set false explicitly in a
# production .env. (Setting it false here would make the AuthZEN tests fail,
# since they evaluate arbitrary body subjects.)
# ALLOW_SUBJECT_OVERRIDE=false
#
# OPA read path equivalent: REQUIRE_TOKEN_FOR_READS gates explicit-subject reads
# (input.subject with no JWT). true = token-only (compose default, production-
# safe); false = trusted-PEP mode. The demo opts into false via env.sh; leave
# commented here. Set true explicitly in a production .env.
# REQUIRE_TOKEN_FOR_READS=true

# ── Condition (ABAC) policy ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# statement_timeout armed on the service roles. It bounds condition evaluation,
# but applies to EVERY query on those connections — size it above your slowest
# legitimate operation (time-travel, broad list_*).
CONDITION_STATEMENT_TIMEOUT=60s
#
# CEL condition language: when truthy, the helper scripts overlay compose-cel.yml
# so the Postgres image is built with the pg_cel extension (extensions/pg-cel)
# and init.sh enables it, unlocking lang='cel' conditions. Off by default (stock
# postgres, sql conditions only). Equivalent to `./bootstrap.sh --cel` /
# `./start.sh --cel`. First build compiles the extension and takes a while.
# PGAUTHZ_CEL=1

# ── Contextual-tuple checks ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Contextual-tuple checks let the caller inject ephemeral tuples; the privilege
# is its own role (authz_contextual_reader), granted to no one by default. If
# set, init.sh GRANTs it to this role — use ONLY a trusted PDP/backend role.
# AUTHZ_CONTEXTUAL_READER_GRANTEE=my_trusted_backend

# ── Misc ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
DEFAULT_STORE=demo
# LOG_LEVEL=info
